June 5, 2022


Hello Dmitri,


Once a month, we outline our comparative view of various sectors in terms o=
f risk adjusted returns.  Following is our current view along with highligh=
ts from our sector reports on each.  As an investor, this data can then be =
used in forward looking strategy, due diligence, as well as investor commun=
ications to help support your investment case to a sector agnostic investor=
.



Following are some interesting highlights across a number of these sectors.



[Table  Description automatically generated]



Following are some highlights across several of these sectors.  Note, links=
 will only work for current research clients.



Lodging - https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16336/download?region=
=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1



Lodging performance has roared back following a difficult start to the year=
 due to Omicron.  Overall U.S. RevPAR is now well above pre-Covid levels, p=
owered by robust leisure demand.



*       Lodging - Insight from Marriot's Earning: https://my.greenstreet.co=
m/research/reports/qt_6010/download?region=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1

o   Marriott (MAR), the largest hotel operator/franchisor in the world with=
 ~1.5 million rooms in its system, reported 1Q22 earnings



[Chart, waterfall chart  Description automatically generated]



SFR/Apartments/Manufactured Housing: https://my.greenstreet.com/research/re=
ports/16334/download?region=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1



SFR is well positioned to weather high inflation and weakening economy; lit=
tle NOI deceleration expected in '23.  MH cost pressures (both opex & G&A) =
have restrained growth; durable demand will eventually garner a premium.



*       Residential Insights - Impact of Rising Rates and Cost of Housing: =
https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16242/download?region=3DNA&appl=
yWaterMark=3D1

     *   The SFR sector seems to provide the best insurance in navigating a=
n environment where inflation and mortgage rates are rising substantially.



[Text  Description automatically generated]



Self Storage: https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16329/download?re=
gion=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1



Storage fundamentals remain strong; our '22 same-store NOI outlook (now ~17=
%) has improved 180 bps.  High input prices, labor costs, and construction =
financing has led to development delays, pushing back new supply.



*       Conference Insights - Warm Weather, Hot Sector: https://my.greenstr=
eet.com/research/reports/16342/download?region=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1

o   Bid-ask spreads appear to be widening, as there have been properties ma=
rketed with aggressive pricing that come back around after initial pricing =
is declined.



[Chart  Description automatically generated with medium confidence]



Data Centers: https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16316/download?re=
gion=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1



Record absorption during 4Q21-1Q22 has temporarily depleted top data center=
 markets of leasable capacity. Vacancy is at record low levels (~1% in Nort=
hern Virginia!) and speculative development

projects (i.e., those with no pre-leasing) no longer pose near-term headwin=
ds.



[Graphical user interface  Description automatically generated with medium =
confidence]



HealthCare (Life Science, Sr Housing, MOB) https://my.greenstreet.com/resea=
rch/reports/16205/download?region=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1



At current levels of demand growth, new supply alone seems unlikely to caus=
e fundamentals to free fall, but it should cause a deceleration in '23 - '2=
4.



[Chart  Description automatically generated]





Industrial: https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16155/download?regi=
on=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1



Strongest in So Cal (+20% in '22) with other coastal markets not far behind



*       Industrial Sector - All in on the Coasts - https://my.greenstreet.c=
om/research/reports/16274/download?region=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1

o   All our industrial fundamental forecasts are currently under review, bu=
t it is safe to say the more pronounced positive revisions to our estimates=
 will occur in coastal markets, especially Southern California.



[Chart, scatter chart  Description automatically generated]





Office: https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16341/download?region=
=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1



Slower economic growth, higher interest rates, and tech hiring slowdown are=
 risks



[Graphical user interface, text  Description automatically generated]





Strip Centers: https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16197/download?r=
egion=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1



Affluent pockets of tertiary markets (e.g. Colorado Springs, CO; Naples, FL=
) performed particularly well.  Out-migration from urban areas to affluent =
tertiary markets was likely the most important driver of outperformance.



[Graphical user interface, text, application, Word  Description automatical=
ly generated]



Towers: https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16292/download?region=
=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1

*       Mobile data demand is strong and continues to fuel new leasing acti=
vity across the tower sector

Net Lease: https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16187/download?regio=
n=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1

*       '22-'24 rent restructuring estimates have been lowered to ~25 bps p=
er year

Malls: https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16175/download?region=3D=
NA&applyWaterMark=3D1

*       Macro Concerns Fueling Lower Forecasts

Gaming: https://my.greenstreet.com/research/reports/16009/download?region=
=3DNA&applyWaterMark=3D1

*       Pent-up demand continues to drive a rebound in Las Vegas operations


Enjoy and if you are not a client and want to take a closer look, please re=
ach out to me.

